04752nam a22005295i 9780774851114DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072004xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748511147 a10.59962/97807748511142doi  a(DE-B1597)661453  a(OCoLC)855907701  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aD810.I5bS54 2004eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a940.53/089/970711 aSheffield, R. Scott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Red Man's on the Warpath :bThe Image of the "Indian" and the Second World War /cR. Scott Sheffield. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b9 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tThe Image of the “Indian” in English Canada, 1930–39 -- tThe “Administrative Indian” as Soldier and Conscript, 1939–45 -- tThe “Public Indian” Goes to War, September 1939–December 1941 -- tWinning the War Only to Lose the Peace? Reconstructing the “Public Indian,” 1943–45 -- tThe “Administrative Indian” at the Threshold of Peace, January-March 1946 -- tInto the Arena: Marshalling the Competing Indian Images in Postwar Canada, 1945–48 -- tWhither the “Indian”? The Special Joint Senate and House of Commons Committee to Reconsider the Indian Act, 1946–48 -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"The red man's on the warpath! The time has come for him to dig up the hatchet and join his paleface brother in his fight to make the world safe for the sacred cause of freedom and democracy." -- Winnipeg Free Press, May 1941 During the Second World War, thousands of First Nations people joined in the national crusade to defend freedom and democracy. High rates of Native enlistment and public demonstrations of patriotism encouraged Canadians to re-examine the roles and status of Native people in Canadian society. The Red Man's on the Warpath explores how wartime symbolism and imagery propelled the "Indian problem" onto the national agenda, and why assimilation remained the goal of post-war Canadian Indian policy -- even though the war required that it be rationalized in new ways. The word "Indian" conjured up a complex framework of visual imagery, stereotypes, and assumptions that enabled English Canadians to explain the place of First Nations people in the national story. Sheffield examines how First Nations people were discussed in both the administrative and public realms. Drawing upon an impressive array of archival records, newspapers, and popular magazines, he tracks continuities and changes in the image of the "Indian" before, during, and immediately after the Second World War. Informed by current academic debates and theoretical perspectives, this book will interest scholars in the fields of Native-Newcomer and race relations, war and society, communications studies, and post-Confederation Canadian history. Sheffield's lively style makes it accessible to a broader readership.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485111440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774851114423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774851114/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eB